 question by analyzing the victims' experiences at each stage of forced relocation: the round-ups and departures from the ghettos, the captivity in trains, and finally, the arrival at the camps. Utilizing a variety of published memoirs and unpublished testimonies, the book argues that victims experienced the train journeys as mobile chambers, comparable in importance to the more studied, fixed locations of persecution, such as ghettos and camps.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xPsychological aspects. 0aPolitical prisonerszAustria. 0aPolitical prisonerszGermany. 0aPrisoners of warzAustria. 0aPrisoners of warzGermany. 0aRailroad trains. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, Jewish. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConcentration camps. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPrisoners and prisonsxPsychological aspects. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh2 aKnowledge Unlatchedefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781785334771?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781785334771zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781785334771/original  a978-3-11-099828-3 Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA